      "role": "user",
      "content": "thanks. i already checked the injectors and they seem okay. i've also checked the fuel pressure and it's within spec. i was thinking maybe a vacuum leak somewhere along the intake manifold? how would i go about testing for that specifically?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "To test for a vacuum leak along the intake manifold, you can use a smoke machine or a propane leak detector. These tools will help you identify any leaks by introducing smoke or propane into the intake system and observing where it escapes. If you don't have access to these tools, you can also perform a visual inspection of the intake manifold and its connections for any signs of damage or wear. Additionally, listen for any unusual noises when the engine is running, as a vacuum leak can often produce a hissing or whistling sound. Remember, dealing with vacuum leaks can be tricky, so if you're not comfortable performing these tests yourself, consider seeking help from a professional mechanic.",
